Fifth Avenue, east side, from East 43rd (right) to 45th (left) Street's, showing prominently the Temple Emanu El. This is at the N. E. corner of 43rd Street, and was erected in 1868. It will be demolished in 1927 and replaced with the office structure, the Lefcourt-National Building.
The fenced plot on the right (S. E. corner of 43rd St.) was the site of the former "Boss" Tweed home. The Postal Life Insurance Co. Bldg. was erected there later.

About 1890

Thru the New York Historical Society

NEG. 4334

North on Fifth Avenue from 43rd Street, showing at right Delmonico's.

Church with statues is Protestant Episcopal Church of the Heavenly Rest.

The frame houses at the extreme right have been demolished and the Harriman National Bank now occupies the property.

1899.

Photograph by Ewing Galloway.

Fifth Avenue, east side, north from 43rd Street.
At extreme right is home of William Marcy Tweed at height of his political infamy (1867-1871).
In centre is Temple Emanu-El.
Large white building at left centre is Harriman National Bank.
The first building to its left is Delmonico's.

1922.

Gift of E. M. Jenks.

43, 41, 35, 33, 27 West 43rd Street, north side, between Sixth and Fifth Avenues. No. 43 is the New York Bar Association, adjoining it at No. 41 is the new Bar Building. No. 33, one of the small buildings, is Fire Engine House No. 65. Adjoining it on the east is the 22-story National Association Building, where the Racquet and Tennis Club used to be before it moved to Park Avenue.

About 1922.

Gift of E. M. Jenks.
5h Ave., e.s., 43rd to 44th St.  1924

(1)
Temple Emanu-El, Fifth Avenue at N.E. corner of 43rd Street. This synagogue, built in 1868, was until its demolition in 1927 one of the city's landmarks. The site is now occupied by the Lefcourt Office Building, and a new Emanu-El has been built on Fifth Avenue at the northeast corner of 65th Street. In this picture the work of demolition is about to begin, as is evidenced by the scaffolding around the church.

August 30, 1927.

P. L. Sperr, Photographer.

(2)
Fifth Avenue at N.W. Corner of 43rd Street, showing demolition of Temple Emanu-El. This picture appeared in the rotagravure section of the New York World for October 9, 1927.

September 26, 1927.

to its removal uptown in 192o.
